description: From the past participle stem of Latin prōtrahō, essentially pro- +‎ tract.

verbs.description: protract (third-person singular simple present protracts, present participle protracting, simple past and past participle protracted)

entries.meaning: To draw out; to extend, especially in duration.
examples: I have protracted my work till most of those whom I wished to please, have sunk into the grave  […]

entries.meaning: (surveying) To draw to a scale; to lay down the lines and angles of, with scale and protractor; to plot.
examples: This is a synopsis of our marches, which, protracted on Burckhardt’s map, gives an error of ten miles.

entries.meaning: To put off to a distant time; to delay; to defer.
examples: to protract a decision or duty
A cat can protract and retract its claws.
